# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: academic-publishing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] An **abstract** is a brief summary of a research article, thesis, review, conference proceeding, or any in-depth analysis of a particular subject and is often used to help the reader quickly ascertain the paper's purpose.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] When used, an abstract always appears at the beginning of a manuscript or typescript, acting as the point-of-entry for any given academic paper or patent application.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Abstracting and indexing services for various academic disciplines are aimed at compiling a body of literature for that particular subject.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The terms ***précis*** or ***synopsis*** are used in some publications to refer to the same thing that other publications might call an "abstract".
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] In management reports, an *executive summary* usually contains more information (and often more sensitive information) than the abstract does.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Academic literature uses the abstract to succinctly communicate complex research.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] An abstract may act as a stand-alone entity instead of a full paper.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] As such, an abstract is used by many organizations as the basis for selecting research that is proposed for presentation in the form of a poster, platform/oral presentation or workshop presentation at an academic conference.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Most bibliographic databases only index abstracts rather than providing the entire text of the paper.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Full texts of scientific papers must often be purchased because of copyright and/or publisher fees and therefore the abstract is a significant selling point for the reprint or electronic form of the full text.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The abstract can convey the main results and conclusions of a scientific article but the full text article must be consulted for details of the methodology, the full experimental results, and a critical discussion of the interpretations and conclusions.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Abstracts are occasionally inconsistent with full reports.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] This has the potential to mislead clinicians who rely solely on the information present in the abstract without consulting the full report.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] An abstract allows one to sift through copious numbers of papers for ones in which the researcher can have more confidence that they will be relevant to their research.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Once papers are chosen based on the abstract, they must be read carefully to be evaluated for relevance.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] It is generally agreed that one must not base reference citations on the abstract alone, but the content of an entire paper.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] This is because abstracts may not be fully representative of the full report or article.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Therefore, basing reference citations solely on the information present in the abstract could be misleading.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] According to the results of a study published in *PLOS Medicine*, the "exaggerated and inappropriate coverage of research findings in the news media" is ultimately related to inaccurately reporting or over-interpreting research results in many abstract conclusions.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The history of abstracting dates back to the point when it was felt necessary to summarise the content of documents in order to make the information contained in them more accessible.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] In Mesopotamia during the early second millennium BCE, clay envelopes designed to protect enclosed cuneiform documents from tampering were inscribed either with the full text of the document or a summary.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] In the Greco-Roman world, many texts were abstracted: summaries of non-fiction works were known as epitomes, and in many cases the only information about works which have not survived to modernity comes from their epitomes which have survived.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Similarly, the text of many ancient Greek and Roman plays commenced with a hypothesis which summed up the play's plot.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Non-literary documents were also abstracted: the Tebtunis papyri found in the Ancient Egyptian town of Tebtunis contain abstracts of legal documents.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] During the Middle Ages, the pages of scholarly texts contained summaries of their contents as marginalia, as did some manuscripts of the Code of Justinian.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The use of abstracts to summarise science originates in the early 1800s, when the secretary of the Royal Society would record brief summaries of talks into the minutes of each meeting, which were referred to as 'abstracts'.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The Royal Society abstracts from 1800 – 1837 were later collated and published in the society's journal *Philosophical Transactions*, with the first group appearing in 1832.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] These abstracts were generally one or more pages long.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Other learned societies adopted similar practices.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The RAS abstracts were between one and three paragraphs long.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] In both cases, these early abstracts were written by the learned society, not the author of the paper.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Perhaps the earliest example of an abstract published alongside the paper it summarises was the 1919 paper *On the Irregularities of Motion of the Foucault Pendulum* published in the *Physical Review* of the American Physical Society, which often published abstracts thereafter.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Abstracts in the United States are protected under copyright law just as any other form of written speech is protected.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Abstract is often expected to tell a complete story of the paper, as for most readers, abstract is the only part of the paper that will be read.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] It should allow the reader to give an elevator pitch of the full paper.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] It may also contain brief references, although some publications' standard style omits references from the abstract, reserving them for the article body (which, by definition, treats the same topics but in more depth).
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Abstract length varies by discipline and publisher requirements.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Typical length ranges from 100 to 500 words, but very rarely more than a page and occasionally just a few words.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] An abstract may or may not have the section title of "abstract" explicitly listed as an antecedent to content.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Sometimes, abstracts are sectioned logically as an overview of what appears in the paper, with any of the following subheadings: Background, Introduction, Objectives, Methods, Results, Discussion, Conclusions.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Abstracts in which these subheadings are explicitly given are often called **structured abstracts**.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Abstracts that comprise one paragraph (no explicit subheadings) are often called **unstructured abstracts**.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Abstracts are important enough that IMRAD is even sometimes recast as AIMRAD.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The **informative abstract**, also known as the **complete abstract**, is a compendious summary of a paper's substance and its background, purpose, methodology, results, and conclusion.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Usually between 100 and 200 words, the informative abstract summarizes the paper's structure, its major topics and key points.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] A format for scientific short reports that is similar to an informative abstract has been proposed in recent years.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Informative abstracts may be viewed as standalone documents.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The **descriptive abstract**, also known as the **limited abstract** or the **indicative abstract**, provides a description of what the paper covers without delving into its substance.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] A descriptive abstract is akin to a table of contents in paragraph form.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] During the late 2000s, due to the influence of computer storage and retrieval systems such as the Internet, some scientific publications, primarily those published by Elsevier, started including graphical abstracts alongside the text abstracts.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The graphic is intended to summarize or be an exemplar for the main thrust of the article.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] It is not intended to be as exhaustive a summary as the text abstract, rather it is supposed to indicate the type, scope, and technical coverage of the article at a glance.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] The use of graphical abstracts has been generally well received by the scientific community.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Moreover, some journals also include video abstracts and animated abstracts made by the authors to easily explain their papers.
[src:academic-publishing/abstract-summary] Various methods can be used to evaluate abstract quality, e.g. rating by readers, checklists, and readability measures (such as Flesch Reading Ease).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Authorship is a primary basis that employers use to evaluate academic personnel for employment, promotion, and tenure.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In academic publishing, authorship of a work is typically claimed by those making intellectual contributions to the research described in the work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] However, many scholarly journals also require that potential authors contribute to the writing of the article about the work, not just the work itself.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Such requirements, as well as other norms around authorship in disciplines, can be controversial.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In these contexts, authorship can encompass activities other than writing the article; a researcher who comes up with an experimental design and analyzes the data may be considered an author, even if she or he had little role in composing the text describing the results.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] According to some standards, even writing the entire article would not constitute authorship unless the writer was also involved in at least one other phase of the project.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Guidelines for assigning authorship vary between institutions and disciplines.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] They may be formally defined or simply cultural norms.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Incorrect assignment of authorship occasionally leads to charges of academic misconduct and sanctions for the violator.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] A 2002 survey of a large sample of researchers who had received funding from the U.S.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] National Institutes of Health revealed that 10% of respondents claimed to have inappropriately assigned authorship credit within the last three years.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] This was the first large scale survey concerning such issues.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In other fields only limited or no empirical data is available.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The natural sciences have no universal standard for authorship, but some major multi-disciplinary journals and institutions have established guidelines for work that they publish.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The American Chemical Society further specifies that authors are those who also "share responsibility and accountability for the results" and the U.S.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] National Academies specify "an author who is willing to take credit for a paper must also bear responsibility for its contents.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In mathematics, the authors are usually listed in alphabetical order (the so-called Hardy-Littlewood Rule).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The medical field defines authorship very narrowly.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] According to the Uniform Requirements for Manuscripts Submitted to Biomedical Journals, designation as an author must satisfy four conditions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Acquisition of funding, or general supervision of the research group alone does not constitute authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Biomedical authorship is prone to various misconducts and disputes.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Many authors – especially those in the middle of the byline – do not fulfill these authorship criteria.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Some medical journals have abandoned the strict notion of author, with the flexible notion of *contributor*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The American Psychological Association (APA) has similar guidelines as medicine for authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] While the APA guidelines list many other forms of contributions to a study that do not constitute authorship, it does state that combinations of these and other tasks may justify authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Like medicine, the APA considers institutional position, such as department chair, insufficient for attributing authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Neither the Modern Languages Association nor the Chicago Manual of Style define requirements for authorship (because usually humanities works are single-authored and the author is responsible for the entire work).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] From the late 17th century to the 1920s, sole authorship was the norm, and the one-paper-one-author model worked well for distributing credit.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Today, shared authorship is common in most academic disciplines, with the exception of the humanities, where sole authorship is still the predominant model.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Between about 1980-2010 the average number of authors in medical papers increased, and perhaps tripled.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In particular types of research, including particle physics, genome sequencing and clinical trials, a paper's author list can run into the hundreds, referred to as "hyperauthorship".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In 1998, the Collider Detector at Fermilab (CDF) adopted a (at that time) highly unorthodox policy for assigning authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] All scientists and engineers working at CDF are added to the standard author list after one year of full-time work; names stay on the list until one year after the worker leaves CDF.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Every publication coming out of CDF uses the entire standard author list, in alphabetical order.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Other big collaborations, including most particle physics experiments, followed this model.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In large, multi-center clinical trials authorship is often used as a reward for recruiting patients.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] A paper published in the New England Journal of Medicine in 1993 reported on a clinical trial conducted in 1,081 hospitals in 15 different countries, involving a total of 41,021 patients.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] There were 972 authors listed in an appendix and authorship was assigned to a group.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In 2015, an article in high-energy physics was published describing the measurement of the mass of the Higgs boson based on collisions in the Large Hadron Collider; the article boasted 5,154 authors, the printed author list needed 24 pages.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Large authors lists have attracted some criticism and are believed to negatively affect all existing ethical issues of authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] They strain guidelines that insist that each author's role be described and that each author is responsible for the validity of the whole work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Such a system treats authorship more as *credit* for scientific service at the facility in general rather that as an identification of specific contributions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] One commentator wrote, "In more than 25 years working as a scientific editor ...
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Alternatively, the increase in multi-authorship is according to a game-theoretic analysis a consequence of the way scientists are evaluated.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Scientists are judged by the number of papers they publish, and by the impact of those papers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Both measures are integrated into the most popular single value measure h -index.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The h -index correlates with winning the Nobel Prize, being accepted for research fellowships and holding positions at top universities.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] When each author claims each paper and each citation as his/her own, papers and citations are multiplied by the number of authors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Since it is common and rational to cite own papers more than others, a high number of coauthors increases not only the number of own papers, but also their impact.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] As result, game rules set by h -index being a decision criterion for success create a zero-sum **h -index ranking game**, where the rational strategy includes maximizing the number of coauthors up to the majority of the researchers in a field.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Data of 189 thousand publications showed that the coauthors' number is strongly correlated with h -index.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Hence, the system rewards heavily multi-authored papers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] This problem is openly acknowledged, and it could easily be "corrected" by dividing each paper and its citations by the number of authors, though this practice has not been widely adopted.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Rules for the order of multiple authors in a list have historically varied significantly between fields of research.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Some fields list authors in order of their degree of involvement in the work, with the most active contributors listed first; other fields, such as mathematics or engineering, sometimes list them alphabetically.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Historically, biologists tended to place a principal investigator (supervisor or lab head) last in an author list whereas organic chemists might have put him or her first.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Research articles in high energy physics, where the author lists can number in the tens to hundreds, often list authors alphabetically.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In the academic fields of economics, business, finance or particle physics, it is also usual to sort the authors alphabetically.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Although listing authors in order of the involvement in the project seems straightforward, it often leads to conflict.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] A study in the *Canadian Medical Association Journal* found that more than two-thirds of 919 corresponding authors disagreed with their coauthors regarding contributions of each author.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Authors' reputations can be damaged if their names appear on a paper that they do not completely understand or with which they were not intimately involved.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Numerous guidelines and customs specify that all co-authors must be able to understand and support a paper's major points.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In a notable case, American stem-cell researcher Gerald Schatten had his name listed on a paper co-authored with Hwang Woo-suk.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] All authors, including co-authors, are usually expected to have made reasonable attempts to check findings submitted for publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In some cases, co-authors of faked research have been accused of inappropriate behavior or research misconduct for failing to verify reports authored by others or by a commercial sponsor.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Examples include the case of Professor Geoffrey Chamberlain named as guest author of papers fabricated by Malcolm Pearce, (Chamberlain was exonerated from collusion in Pearce's deception) and the co-authors of Jan Hendrik Schön at Bell Laboratories.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] More recent cases include Charles Nemeroff, former editor-in-chief of *Neuropsychopharmacology*, and the so-called Sheffield Actonel affair.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Additionally, authors are expected to keep all study data for later examination even after publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Both scientific and academic censure can result from a failure to keep primary data; the case of Ranjit Chandra of Memorial University of Newfoundland provides an example of this.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Many scientific journals also require that authors provide information to allow readers to determine whether the authors may have commercial or non-commercial conflicts of interest.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Outlined in the author disclosure statement for the *American Journal of Human Biology*, this is a policy more common in scientific fields where funding often comes from corporate sources.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Authors are also commonly required to provide information about ethical aspects of research, particularly where research involves human or animal participants or use of biological material.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Provision of incorrect information to journals may be regarded as misconduct.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Financial pressures on universities have encouraged this type of misconduct.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The majority of recent cases of alleged misconduct involving undisclosed conflicts of interest or failure of the authors to have seen scientific data involve collaborative research between scientists and biotechnology companies.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] A possible measure against honorary authorships has been implemented by some scientific journals, in particular by the *Nature* journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] They demand that each new manuscript must include a statement of responsibility that specifies the contribution of every author.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The level of detail varies between the disciplines.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Senior persons may still make some vague claim to have "supervised the project", for example, even if they were only in the formal position of a supervisor without having delivered concrete contributions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] (The truth content of such statements is usually not checked by independent persons.) However, the need to describe contributions can at least be expected to somewhat reduce honorary authorships.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In addition, it may help to identify the perpetrator in a case of scientific fraud.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] More specific types of honorary authorship are gift, guest and rolling authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] **Gift** authorship consists of authorship obtained by the offer of another author (honorary or not) with objectives that are beyond the research article itself or are ulterior, as promotion or favor.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Researchers found that there are cultural differences in how acceptable people perceive this sort of unmerited gift authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] For example, graduate students in Denmark said it was less acceptable to add a co-author who did not help with the paper than students in China.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Ghost authorship has been linked to partnerships between industry and higher education.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Two-thirds of industry-initiated randomized trials may have evidence of ghost authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Ghost authorship is considered problematic because it may be used to obscure the participation of researchers with conflicts of interest.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Litigation against the pharmaceutical company, Merck over health concerns related to use of their drug, Rofecoxib (brand name Vioxx), revealed examples of ghost authorship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Merck routinely paid medical writing companies to prepare journal manuscripts, and subsequently recruited external, academically affiliated researchers to pose as the authors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Authors are sometimes included in a list without their permission.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Even if this is done with the benign intention to acknowledge some contributions, it is problematic since authors carry responsibility for correctness and thus need to have the opportunity to check the manuscript and possibly demand changes.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Researchers can pay to intentionally and dishonestly list themselves as authors on papers they have not contributed to, usually by using an academic paper mill which specializes in authorship sales.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Authors occasionally forgo claiming authorship, for a number of reasons.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Historically some authors have published anonymously to shield themselves when presenting controversial claims.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] A key example is Robert Chambers' anonymous publication of Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation, a speculative, pre-Darwinian work on the origins of life and the cosmos.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The book argued for an evolutionary view of life in the same spirit as the late Frenchman Jean-Baptiste Lamarck.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Lamarck had long been discredited among intellectuals by this time and evolutionary (or development) theories were exceedingly unpopular, except among the political radicals, materialists, and atheists – Chambers hoped to avoid Lamarck's fate.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In the 18th century, Émilie du Châtelet began her career as a scientific author by submitting a paper in an annual competition held by the French Academy of Sciences; papers in this competition were submitted anonymously.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Initially presenting her work without claiming authorship allowed her to have her work judged by established scientists while avoiding the bias against women in the sciences.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] She did not win the competition, but eventually her paper was published alongside the winning submissions, under her real name.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Scientists and engineers working in corporate and military organizations are often restricted from publishing and claiming authorship of their work because their results are considered secret property of the organization that employs them.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] One notable example is that of William Sealy Gosset, who was forced to publish his work in statistics under the pseudonym "Student" due to his employment at the Guinness brewery.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Another account describes the frustration of physicists working in nuclear weapons programs at the Lawrence Livermore Laboratory – years after making a discovery they would read of the same phenomenon being "discovered" by a physicist unaware of the original, secret discovery of the phenomenon.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Satoshi Nakamoto is a pseudonym of a still unknown author or authors' group behind a white paper about bitcoin.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Group authorship, also known as corporate, team, or consortium authorship, involves listing a collective entity (e.g., team, project, corporation, or consortium) as the author in the byline.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Equal co-authorship refers to crediting multiple authors as having made "equal contributions" to a paper, often as co-first or co-corresponding authors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] This practice has become more common in recent years.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Despite its rise, equal co-authorship presents ethical and practical challenges.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] For instance, it can be difficult to assess whether contributions were truly equal, and tensions might arise about whose name should appear first (the sequence of equal authors).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Some argue that equal co-authorship helps resolve tensions and offers fair recognition of significant contributions, especially in collaborative projects.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] However, even in truly equal scenarios, one author often becomes more prominent, leading to additional complexities about authorship order and responsibilities.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] The inconsistent recognition of equal co-authorship by journals and academic institutions, along with the lack of standardized policies, further complicates its evaluation in tenure, promotion, and funding decisions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] There have been some cases of non-human animals being credited as authors on academic papers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] One of the most famous cases may be that of FDC Willard, a co-author of an influential paper on atomic behavior who happened to be the pet cat of the main author, Jack Hetherington.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] This paper has been cited over 100 times as of 2025.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] In these cases, the animal author would not have a legitimate claim to authorship, given that they cannot take responsibility for the content of the paper and consent to its submission.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Artificial intelligence systems have been credited with authorship on a handful of academic publications, however, many publishers disallow this on the grounds that "they cannot take responsibility for the content and integrity of scientific papers".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-authorship] Instead, most academic journals require authors to disclose use of AI assistance in the acknowledgements or a special section of the paper.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] An **academic discipline** or **academic field** is a subdivision of knowledge that is taught and researched at the college or university level.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Disciplines are defined (in part) and recognized by the academic journals in which research is published, and the learned societies and academic departments or faculties within colleges and universities to which their practitioners belong.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Academic disciplines are conventionally divided into the humanities (including philosophy, languages, art and cultural studies), the natural sciences (such as physics, chemistry, and biology); and the formal sciences like mathematics and computer science.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The social sciences are sometimes considered a fourth category.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] It is also known as a *field of study*, *field of inquiry*, *research field* and *branch of knowledge*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The different terms are used in different countries and fields.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Individuals associated with academic disciplines are commonly referred to as *experts* or *specialists*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Others, who may have studied liberal arts or systems theory rather than concentrating in a specific academic discipline, are classified as *generalists*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] For example, professionals may encounter trouble communicating across academic disciplines because of differences in jargon, concepts, or methodology.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Some researchers believe that academic disciplines may, in the future, be replaced by what is known as Mode 2 or "post-academic science", which involves the acquisition of cross-disciplinary knowledge through the collaboration of specialists from various academic disciplines.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The University of Paris in 1231 consisted of four faculties:- Theology, Medicine, Canon Law and Arts.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Educational institutions originally used the term "discipline" to catalog and archive the new and expanding body of information produced by the scholarly community.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Disciplinary designations originated in German universities during the beginning of the nineteenth century.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] In the early twentieth century, new academic disciplines such as education and psychology were added.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] In the 1970s and 1980s, there was an explosion of new academic disciplines focusing on specific themes, such as media studies, women's studies, and Africana studies.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Many academic disciplines designed as preparation for careers and professions, such as nursing, hospitality management, and corrections, also emerged in the universities.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Finally, interdisciplinary scientific fields of study such as biochemistry and geophysics gained prominence as their contribution to knowledge became widely recognized.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Some new disciplines, such as public administration, can be found in more than one disciplinary setting; some public administration programs are associated with business schools (thus emphasizing management), while others are linked to political science (emphasizing policy analysis).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] As the twentieth century approached, these designations were gradually adopted by other countries and became the accepted conventional subjects.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] However, these designations differed between various countries.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] In the twentieth century, the natural science disciplines included: physics, chemistry, biology, geology, and astronomy.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The social science disciplines included: economics, politics, sociology, and psychology.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Prior to the twentieth century, categories were broad and general, which was expected due to the lack of interest in science at the time.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Most practitioners of science were amateurs and were referred to as "natural historians" and "natural philosophers"—labels that date back to Aristotle—instead of "scientists".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Natural history referred to what we now call life sciences and natural philosophy referred to the current physical sciences.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Prior to the twentieth century, few opportunities existed for science as an occupation outside the educational system.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Higher education provided the institutional structure for scientific investigation, as well as economic support for research and teaching.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Soon, the volume of scientific information rapidly increased and researchers realized the importance of concentrating on smaller, narrower fields of scientific activity.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Because of this narrowing, scientific specializations emerged.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] As these specializations developed, modern scientific disciplines in universities also improved their sophistication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Eventually, academia's identified disciplines became the foundations for scholars of specific specialized interests and expertise.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] An influential critique of the concept of academic disciplines came from Michel Foucault in his 1975 book, *Discipline and Punish*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Communities of academic disciplines can be found outside academia within corporations, government agencies, and independent organizations, where they take the form of associations of professionals with common interests and specific knowledge.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Such communities include corporate think tanks, NASA, and IUPAC.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Communities such as these exist to benefit the organizations affiliated with them by providing specialized new ideas, research, and findings.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Nations at various developmental stages will find the need for different academic disciplines during different times of growth.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] A newly developing nation will likely prioritize government, political matters and engineering over those of the humanities, arts and social sciences.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] On the other hand, a well-developed nation may be capable of investing more in the arts and social sciences.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Communities of academic disciplines would contribute at varying levels of importance during different stages of development.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] These categories explain how the different academic disciplines interact with one another.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Multidisciplinary (or pluridisciplinary) knowledge is associated with more than one existing academic discipline or profession.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] A multidisciplinary community or project is made up of people from different academic disciplines and professions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] One key question is how well the challenge can be decomposed into subparts, and then addressed via the distributed knowledge in the community.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The lack of shared vocabulary between people and communication overhead can sometimes be an issue in these communities and projects.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] If challenges of a particular type need to be repeatedly addressed so that each one can be properly decomposed, a multidisciplinary community can be exceptionally efficient and effective.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] There are many examples of a particular idea appearing in different academic disciplines, all of which came about around the same time.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] One example of this scenario is the shift from the approach of focusing on sensory awareness of the whole, "an attention to the 'total field'", a "sense of the whole pattern, of form and function as a unity", an "integral idea of structure and configuration".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] This has happened in art (in the form of cubism), physics, poetry, communication and educational theory.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] According to Marshall McLuhan, this paradigm shift was due to the passage from the era of mechanization, which brought sequentiality, to the era of the instant speed of electricity, which brought simultaneity.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Multidisciplinary approaches also encourage people to help shape the innovation of the future.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The political dimensions of forming new multidisciplinary partnerships to solve the so-called societal Grand Challenges were presented in the Innovation Union and in the European Framework Programme, the Horizon 2020 operational overlay.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Innovation across academic disciplines is considered the pivotal foresight of the creation of new products, systems, and processes for the benefit of all societies' growth and wellbeing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Regional examples such as Biopeople and industry-academia initiatives in translational medicine such as SHARE.ku.dk in Denmark provide evidence of the successful endeavour of multidisciplinary innovation and facilitation of the paradigm shift.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] In practice, transdisciplinary can be thought of as the union of all interdisciplinary efforts.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] While interdisciplinary teams may be creating new knowledge that lies between several existing disciplines, a transdisciplinary team is more holistic and seeks to relate all disciplines into a coherent whole.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Cross-disciplinary knowledge is that which explains aspects of one discipline in terms of another.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Common examples of cross-disciplinary approaches are studies of the physics of music or the politics of literature.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Bibliometrics can be used to map several issues in relation to disciplines, for example, the flow of ideas within and among disciplines (Lindholm-Romantschuk, 1998) or the existence of specific national traditions within disciplines.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] Scholarly impact and influence of one discipline on another may be understood by analyzing the flow of citations.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The Bibliometrics approach is described as straightforward because it is based on simple counting.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The method is also objective but the quantitative method may not be compatible with a qualitative assessment and therefore manipulated.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-discipline] The number of citations is dependent on the number of persons working in the same domain instead of inherent quality or published result's originality.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Before the advent of the Internet, it was difficult for scholars to distribute articles giving their research results.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Historically publishers performed services including proofreading, typesetting, copy editing, printing, and worldwide distribution.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In modern times all researchers became expected to give the publishers digital copies of their work which needed no further processing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For digital distribution printing was unnecessary, copying was free, and worldwide distribution happens online instantly.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In science journal publishing, Internet technology enabled the Big Five major scientific publishers—Elsevier, Springer, Wiley, Taylor and Francis and American Chemical Society—to cut their expenditures such that they could consistently generate profits of over 35% per year.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In 2017 these five published 56% of all journal articles.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The remaining 44% were published by over 200 small publishers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The Internet made it easier for researchers to do work which had previously been done by publishers, and some people began to feel that they did not need to pay for the services of publishers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] This perception was a problem for publishers, who stated that their services were still necessary at the rates they asked.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Critics began to describe publishers' practices with terms such as "corporate scam" and "racket".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Scholars sometimes obtain articles from fellow scholars through unofficial channels, such as posting requests on Twitter using the hashtag "#icanhazpdf" (a play on the I Can Has Cheezburger? meme), to avoid paying publishers' access charges.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In 2004, there were reports in British media of a "revolution in academic publishing" which would make research freely available online but many scientists continued to publish their work in the traditional big name journals like *Nature*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For a short time in 2012, the name Academic Spring, inspired by the Arab Spring, was used to indicate movements by academics, researchers, and scholars opposing the restrictive copyright and circulation of traditional academic journals and promoting free access online instead.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The barriers to free access for recent scientific research became a hot topic in 2012, after a blog post by mathematician Timothy Gowers went viral in January.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] According to the *Financial Times*, the movement was named by Dennis Johnson of Melville House Publishing, though scientist Mike Taylor has suggested the name came from *The Economist*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Mike Taylor argued that the Academic Spring may have some unexpected results beyond the obvious benefits.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Referring to work by the biophysicist Cameron Neylon, he says that, because modern science is now more dependent on well-functioning networks than individuals, making information freely available may help computer-based analyses to provide opportunities for major scientific breakthroughs.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Government and university officials have welcomed the prospect of saving on subscriptions which have been rising in cost, while universities' budgets have been shrinking.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Mark Walport, the director of Wellcome Trust, has indicated that science sponsors do not mind having to fund publication in addition to the research.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Although it has some historical precedent, open access became desired in response to the advent of electronic publishing as part of a broader desire for academic journal publishing reform.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Electronic publishing created new benefits as compared to paper publishing but beyond that, it contributed to causing problems in traditional publishing models.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Rather than applying traditional notions of copyright to academic publications, readers should be free to build upon the research of others.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Publications should be libre or "free to build upon".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Everyone should have greater awareness of the serious social problems caused by restricting access to academic research.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Everyone should recognize that there are serious economic challenges for the future of academic publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Even though open access models are problematic, traditional publishing models definitely are not sustainable and something radical needs to change immediately.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Moore proposes designing multiple infrastructural interventions to facilitate experiments in collectivity.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Open access also has ambitions beyond merely granting access to academic publications, as access to research is only a tool for helping people achieve other goals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Open access advances scholarly pursuits in the fields of open data, open government, open educational resources, free and open-source software, and open science, among others.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The motivations for academic journal publishing reform include the ability of computers to store large amounts of information, the advantages of giving more researchers access to preprints, and the potential for interactivity between researchers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Various studies showed that the demand for open access research was such that freely available articles consistently had impact factors which were higher than articles published under restricted access.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Some universities reported that modern "package deal" subscriptions were too costly for them to maintain, and that they would prefer to subscribe to journals individually to save money.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The problems which led to discussion about academic publishing reform have been considered in the context of what provision of open access might provide.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The pricing crisis does not only mean strain to budgets, but also that researchers actually are losing access to journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Not even the wealthiest libraries in the world are able to afford all the journals that their users are demanding, and less rich libraries are severely harmed by lack of access to journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Libraries are cutting their book budgets to pay for academic journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Libraries do not own electronic journals in permanent archival form as they do paper copies, so if they have to cancel a subscription then they lose all subscribed journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] This did not happen with paper journals, and yet costs historically have been higher for electronic versions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Academic publishers get essential assets from their subscribers in a way that other publishers do not.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Authors donate the texts of academic journals to the publishers and grant rights to publish them, and editors and referees donate peer-review to validate the articles.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The people writing the journals are questioning the increased pressure put upon them to pay higher prices for the journal produced by their community.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Conventional publishers are using a business model which requires access barriers and creates artificial scarcity.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] All publishers need revenue, but open access promises models in which scarcity is fundamental to raising revenue.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Scholarly publishing depends heavily on government policy, public subsidies, gift economy, and anti-competitive practices, yet all of these things are in conflict with the conventional academic publishing model of restricting access to works.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Toll access journals compete more for authors to donate content to them than they compete for subscribers to pay for the work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] This is because every scholarly journal has a natural monopoly over the information of its field.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Because of this, the market for pricing journals does not have feedback because it is outside of traditional market forces, and the prices have no control to drive it to serve the needs of the market.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Besides the natural monopoly, there is supporting evidence that prices are artificially inflated to benefit publishers while harming the market.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Evidence includes the trend of large publishers to have accelerating prices increases greater than small publishers, when in traditional markets high volume and high sales enables cost savings and lower prices.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Conventional publishers fund "content protection" actions which restrict and police content sharing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For-profit publishers have economic incentives to decrease rates of rejected articles so that they publish more content to sell.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] No such market force exists if selling content for money is not a motivating factor.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Many researchers are unaware that it might be possible for them to have all the research articles they need, and just accept it as fate that they will always be without some of the articles they would like to read.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Access to toll-access journals is not scaling with increases in research and publishing, and the academic publishers are under market forces to restrict increases in publishing and indirectly because of that they are restricting the growth of research.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Publishers state that if profit was not a consideration in the pricing of journals then the cost of accessing those journals would not substantially change.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Publishers also state that they add value to publications in many ways, and without academic publishing as an institution the readership would miss these services and fewer people would have access to articles.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Critics of open access have suggested that by itself, this is not a solution to scientific publishing's most serious problem – it simply changes the paths through which ever-increasing sums of money flow.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Evidence for this does exist and for example, Yale University ended its financial support of BioMed Central's Open Access Membership program effective July 27, 2007.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Opponents of the open access model see publishers as a part of the scholarly information chain and view a pay-for-access model as being necessary in ensuring that publishers are adequately compensated for their work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Scholarly journal publishers that support pay-for-access claim that the "gatekeeper" role they play, maintaining a scholarly reputation, arranging for peer review, and editing and indexing articles, require economic resources that are not supplied under an open access model.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Conventional journal publishers may also lose customers to open access publishers who compete with them.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The Partnership for Research Integrity in Science and Medicine (PRISM), a lobbying organization formed by the Association of American Publishers (AAP), is opposed to the open access movement.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] PRISM and AAP have lobbied against the increasing trend amongst funding organizations to require open publication, describing it as "government interference" and a threat to peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For researchers, publishing an article in a reputable scientific journal is perceived as being beneficial to one's reputation among scientific peers and in advancing one's academic career.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] There is a concern that the perception of open access journals do not have the same reputation, which will lead to less publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Park and Qin discuss the perceptions that academics have with regard to open access journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Journal article authors are generally not directly financially compensated for their work beyond their institutional salaries and the indirect benefits that an enhanced reputation provides in terms of institutional funding, job offers, and peer collaboration.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] There are those, for example PRISM, who think that open access is unnecessary or even harmful.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] David Goodman argued that there is no need for those outside major academic institutions to have access to primary publications, at least in some fields.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For instance in Australia, 80% of research funding comes through taxes, whereas in Japan and Switzerland, only approximately 10% is from the public coffers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] For various reasons open access journals have been established by predatory publishers who seek to use the model to make money without regard to producing a quality journal.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The causes of predatory open access publishing include the low barrier to creating the appearance of a legitimate digital journal and funding models which may include author publishing costs rather than subscription sales.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] University librarian Jeffrey Beall published a "List of Predatory Publishers" and an accompanying methodology for identifying publishers who have editorial and financial practices which are contrary to the ideal of good research publishing practices.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The Public Library of Science is a nonprofit open-access scientific publishing project aimed at creating a library of open access journals and other scientific literature under an open content license.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The petition collected 34,000 signatures but the publishers took no strong response to the demands.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Shortly thereafter, the Public Library of Science was founded as an alternative to traditional publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] HINARI is a 2002 project of the World Health Organization and major publishers to enable developing countries to access collections of biomedical and health literature online at reduced subscription costs.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The Research Works Act was a bill of the United States Congress which would have prohibited all laws which would require an open access mandate when US-government-funded researchers published their work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The proposers of the law stated that it would "ensure the continued publication and integrity of peer-reviewed research works by the private sector".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] This followed other similar proposed measures such as the Fair Copyright in Research Works Act.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] These attempts to limit free access to such material are controversial and have provoked lobbying for and against by numerous interested parties such as the Association of American Publishers and the American Library Association.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Critics of the law stated that it was the moment that "academic publishers gave up all pretence of being on the side of scientists." In February 2012, Elsevier withdrew its support for the bill.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Following this statement, the sponsors of the bill announced they will also withdraw their support.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In January 2012, Cambridge mathematician Timothy Gowers, started a boycott of journals published by Elsevier, in part a reaction to their support for the *Research Works Act*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In response to an angry blog post by Gowers, the website *The Cost of Knowledge* was launched by a sympathetic reader.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] An online petition called *The Cost of Knowledge* was set up by fellow mathematician Tyler Neylon, to gather support for the boycott.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] By early April 2012, it had been signed by over eight thousand academics.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] As of mid-June 2012, the number of signatories exceeded 12,000.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] In May 2012, a group of open-access activists formed the Access2Research initiative that went on to launch a petition to the White House to "require free access over the Internet to journal articles arising from taxpayer-funded research".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] The petition was signed by over 25,000 people within two weeks, which entitled it to an official response from the White House.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Since 1998, PKP has been developing free open source software platforms for managing and publishing peer-reviewed open access journals and monographs, with Open Journal Systems used by more than 7,000 active journals in 2013.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] 2013 Nobel Prize winner Randy Schekman called for a boycott of traditional academic journals including *Nature*, *Cell*, and *Science*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Instead he promoted the open access journal *eLife*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Initiative for Open Citations is a CrossRef initiative for improved citation analysis.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] It was supported by majority of the publishers effective from April 2017.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Diamond open access journals have been promoted as the ultimate solution to serials crisis.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Under this model, neither the authors nor the readers pay for access or publication, and the resources required to run the journal are provided by scientists on a voluntary basis, by governments or by philanthropic grants.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-journal-publishing-reform] Although the Diamond OA model turned out to be successful in creating a large number of journals, the percentage of publications in such journals remains low, possibly due to a low prestige of these new journals and due to concerns with their long-term viability.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Academic peer review requires a community of experts in a given (and often narrowly defined) academic field, who are qualified and able to perform reasonably impartial review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Impartial review, especially of work in less narrowly defined or inter-disciplinary fields, may be difficult to accomplish, and the significance (good or bad) of an idea may never be widely appreciated among its contemporaries.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Peer review is generally considered necessary to academic quality and is used in most major scholarly journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] However, peer review does not prevent publication of invalid research, and as experimentally controlled studies of this process are difficult to arrange, direct evidence that peer review improves the quality of published papers is scarce.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] One recent analysis of randomized controlled trial abstracts found that editorial and peer review processes led to substantive improvements between submission and publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The first record of an editorial pre-publication peer-review is from 1665 by Henry Oldenburg, the founding editor of *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society* at the Royal Society of London.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The first peer-reviewed publication might have been the *Medical Essays and Observations* published by the Royal Society of Edinburgh in 1731.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The present-day peer-review system evolved from this 18th-century process, began to involve external reviewers in the mid-19th-century, and did not become commonplace until the mid-20th-century.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Peer review became a touchstone of the scientific method, but until the end of the 19th century was often performed directly by an editor-in-chief or editorial committee.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Editors of scientific journals at that time made publication decisions without seeking outside input, i.e. an external panel of reviewers, giving established authors latitude in their journalistic discretion.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For example, Albert Einstein's four revolutionary *Annus Mirabilis* papers in the 1905 issue of *Annalen der Physik* were evaluated by the journal's editor-in-chief, Max Planck, and its co-editor, Wilhelm Wien, both future Nobel prize winners and together experts on the topics of these papers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] While some medical journals started to systematically appoint external reviewers, it is only since the middle of the 20th century that this practice has spread widely and that external reviewers have been given some visibility within academic journals, including being thanked by authors and editors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] A 2003 editorial in *Nature* stated that, in the early 20th century, "the burden of proof was generally on the opponents rather than the proponents of new ideas." *Nature* itself instituted formal peer review only in 1967.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Journals such as *Science* and the American Journal of Medicine increasingly relied on external reviewers in the 1950s and 1960s, in part to reduce the editorial workload.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In the 20th century, peer review also became common for science funding allocations.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] This process appears to have developed independently from that of editorial peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Pragmatically, peer review refers to the work done during the screening of submitted manuscripts.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] This process encourages authors to meet the accepted standards of their discipline and reduces the dissemination of irrelevant findings, unwarranted claims, unacceptable interpretations, and personal views.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Publications that have not undergone peer review are likely to be regarded with suspicion by academic scholars and professionals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Non-peer-reviewed work does not contribute, or contributes less, to the academic credit of a scholar (such as the h-index), although this heavily depends on the field.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] It is difficult and time-consuming for authors and researchers, whether individually or in a team, to spot and provide feedback on every mistake or flaw in a complicated piece of work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] This is not necessarily a reflection on those concerned, but because with a new and perhaps eclectic subject, an opportunity for improvement may be more obvious to someone with special expertise or who simply looks at it with a fresh eye.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Therefore, showing work to others increases the probability that weaknesses will be identified and improved.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For both grant-funding and publication in a scholarly journal, it is also normally a requirement that the subject is both novel and substantial.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The decision whether or not to publish a scholarly article, or what should be modified before publication, ultimately lies with the publisher (editor-in-chief or the editorial board) to which the manuscript has been submitted.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Similarly, the decision whether or not to fund a proposed project rests with an official of the funding agency.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] These individuals usually refer to the opinion of one or more reviewers in making their decision.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Reviewers are often anonymous and independent.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] However, some reviewers may choose to waive their anonymity, and in other limited circumstances, such as the examination of a formal complaint against the referee, or a court order, the reviewer's identity may have to be disclosed.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Anonymity may be unilateral or reciprocal (single- or double-blinded reviewing).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Since reviewers are normally selected from experts in the fields discussed in the article, the process of peer review helps to keep some invalid or unsubstantiated claims out of the body of published research and knowledge.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Scholars will read published articles outside their limited area of detailed expertise, and then rely, to some degree, on the peer-review process to have provided reliable and credible research that they can build upon for subsequent or related research.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Significant scandal ensues when an author is found to have falsified the research included in an article, as other scholars, and the field of study itself, may have relied upon the invalid research.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For US universities, peer reviewing of books before publication is a requirement for full membership of the Association of American University Presses.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In the case of proposed publications, the publisher (editor-in-chief or the editorial board, often with assistance of corresponding or associate editors) sends advance copies of an author's work or ideas to researchers or scholars who are experts in the field (known as "referees" or "reviewers").
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Communication is nowadays normally by e-mail or through a web-based manuscript processing system such as ScholarOne, Scholastica, or Open Journal Systems.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Depending on the field of study and on the specific journal, there are usually one to three referees for a given article.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For example, Springer states that there are two or three reviewers per article.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] An editor evaluates the manuscript to judge whether the paper will be passed on to journal referees.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] At this phase many articles receive a "desk reject", that is, the editor chooses not to pass along the article.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The authors may or may not receive a letter of explanation.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Desk rejection is intended to be a streamlined process so that editors may move past nonviable manuscripts quickly and provide authors with the opportunity to pursue a more suitable journal.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] If "no" to any of these, the manuscript receives a desk rejection.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For example, in 2017 researchers at the World Bank compiled rejection rates of several global economics journals; the desk rejection rate ranged from 21% (*Economic Lacea*) to 66% (*Journal of Development Economics*).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The American Psychological Association publishes rejection rates for several major publications in the field, and although they do not specify whether the rejection is pre- or post- desk evaluation, their figures in 2016 ranged from a low of 49% to a high of 90%.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] If the paper is not desk rejected, the editors send the manuscript to the referees, who are chosen for their expertise and distance from the authors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] At this point, referees may reject, accept without changes (rare) or instruct the authors to revise and resubmit.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Reasons vary for acceptance of an article by editors, but Elsevier published an article where three editors weigh in on factors that drive article acceptance.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] These factors include whether the manuscript: delivers "new insight into an important issue", will be useful to practitioners, advances or proposes a new theory, raises new questions, has appropriate methods and conclusion, presents a good argument based on the literature, and tells a good story.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] One editor notes that he likes papers that he "wished he'd done" himself.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] These referees each return an evaluation of the work to the editor, noting weaknesses or problems along with suggestions for improvement.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Typically, most of the referees' comments are eventually seen by the author, though a referee can also send 'for your eyes only' comments to the publisher; scientific journals observe this convention almost universally.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The editor then evaluates the referees' comments, her or his own opinion of the manuscript before passing a decision back to the author(s), usually with the referees' comments.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Referees' evaluations usually include an explicit recommendation of what to do with the manuscript or proposal, often chosen from options provided by the journal or funding agency.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] During this process, the role of the referees is advisory.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The editor(s) is typically under no obligation to accept the opinions of the referees.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] However, the editor will most often follow the advice of the referees.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Furthermore, the referees in scientific publication do not act as a group, do not communicate with each other, and typically are not aware of each other's identities or evaluations.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Proponents argue that if the reviewers of a paper are unknown to each other, the editor(s) can more easily verify the objectivity of the reviews.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] There is usually no requirement that the referees achieve consensus, with the decision instead often made by the editor(s) based on her best judgement of the arguments.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In situations where multiple referees disagree substantially about the quality of a work, there are a number of strategies for reaching a decision.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The paper may be rejected outright, or the editor may choose which reviewer's point the authors should address.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] When a publisher receives very positive and very negative reviews for the same manuscript, the editor will often solicit one or more additional reviews as a tie-breaker.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] As another strategy in the case of ties, the publisher may invite authors to reply to a referee's criticisms and permit a compelling rebuttal to break the tie.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] If a publisher does not feel confident to weigh the persuasiveness of a rebuttal, the publisher may solicit a response from the referee who made the original criticism.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] An editor may convey communications back and forth between authors and a referee, in effect allowing them to debate a point.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Even in these cases, however, publishers do not allow multiple referees to confer with each other, though each reviewer may often see earlier comments submitted by other reviewers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The goal of the process is explicitly not to reach consensus or to persuade anyone to change their opinions, but instead to provide material for an informed editorial decision.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] One early study regarding referee disagreement found that agreement was greater than chance, if not much greater than chance, on six of seven article attributes (e.g. literature review and final recommendation to publish), but this study was small and it was conducted on only one journal.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] At least one study has found that reviewer disagreement is not common, but this study is also small and on only one journal.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Traditionally, reviewers would often remain anonymous to the authors, but this standard varies both with time and with academic field.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In some academic fields, most journals offer the reviewer the option of remaining anonymous or not, or a referee may opt to sign a review, thereby relinquishing anonymity.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Published papers sometimes contain, in the acknowledgments section, thanks to anonymous or named referees who helped improve the paper.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For example, Nature journals provide this option.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Sometimes authors may exclude certain reviewers: one study conducted on the *Journal of Investigative Dermatology* found that excluding reviewers doubled the chances of article acceptance.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Some scholars are uncomfortable with this idea, arguing that it distorts the scientific process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Others argue that it protects against referees who are biased in some manner (e.g. professional rivalry, grudges).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In some cases, authors can choose referees for their manuscripts.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] *mSphere*, an open-access journal in microbial science, has moved to this model.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Editor-in-Chief Mike Imperiale says this process is designed to reduce the time it takes to review papers and permit the authors to choose the most appropriate reviewers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] But a scandal in 2015 shows how this choosing reviewers can encourage fraudulent reviews.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Fake reviews were submitted to the *Journal of the Renin-Angiotensin-Aldosterone System* in the names of author-recommended reviewers, causing the journal to eliminate this option.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] If the manuscript has not been rejected during peer review, it returns to the authors for revisions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] During this phase, the authors address the concerns raised by reviewers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] William Stafford Noble offers ten rules for responding to reviewers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In economics, some scholars have argued that the revision stage has expanded from evaluation into excessive improvement demands.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] A 2024 review of economics peer review described referee overreach and excessive revisions as contributing to longer papers and slower publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] At a journal or book publisher, the task of picking reviewers typically falls to an editor.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] When a manuscript arrives, an editor solicits reviews from scholars or other experts who may or may not have already expressed a willingness to referee for that journal or book division.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Granting agencies typically recruit a panel or committee of reviewers in advance of the arrival of applications.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Referees are supposed to inform the editor of any conflict of interests that might arise.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Journals or individual editors may invite a manuscript's authors to name people whom they consider qualified to referee their work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For some journals this is a requirement of submission.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Authors are sometimes also given the opportunity to name natural candidates who should be *disqualified*, in which case they may be asked to provide justification (typically expressed in terms of conflict of interest).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Editors solicit author input in selecting referees because academic writing typically is very specialized.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Editors often oversee many specialties, and can not be experts in all of them.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] But after an editor selects referees from the pool of candidates, the editor typically is obliged not to disclose the referees' identities to the authors, and in scientific journals, to each other.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Policies on such matters differ among academic disciplines.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] One difficulty with respect to some manuscripts is that, there may be few scholars who truly qualify as experts, people who have themselves done work similar to that under review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] This can frustrate the goals of reviewer anonymity and avoidance of conflicts of interest.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Low-prestige or local journals and granting agencies that award little money are especially handicapped with regard to recruiting experts.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] A potential hindrance in recruiting referees is that they are usually not paid, largely because doing so would itself create a conflict of interest.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Also, reviewing takes time away from their main activities, such as his or her own research.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] To the would-be recruiter's advantage, most potential referees are authors themselves, or at least readers, who know that the publication system requires that experts donate their time.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Serving as a referee can even be a condition of a grant, or professional association membership.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In general, because of the explosion of the electronic information and the disproportionate increase in journal number versus the steady increase in the number of scientists has created a peer review crisis.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The system currently in place is not responding to modern needs and will inevitably perish, unless radical reforms are made promptly.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The academic system should revolutionize and establish strict peer review activity criteria essential for promotion and tenure, based on established universal metrics.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] That is, reward reviewers academically as it rewards researchers, which is currently not the case.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Referees have the opportunity to prevent work that does not meet the standards of the field from being published, which is a position of some responsibility.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Editors are at a special advantage in recruiting a scholar when they have overseen the publication of his or her work, or if the scholar is one who hopes to submit manuscripts to that editor's publishing entity in the future.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Granting agencies, similarly, tend to seek referees among their present or former grantees.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] With independent peer review services the author usually retains the right to the work throughout the peer review process, and may choose the most appropriate journal to submit the work to.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Peer review services may also provide advice or recommendations on most suitable journals for the work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Journals may still want to perform an independent peer review, without the potential conflict of interest that financial reimbursement may cause, or the risk that an author has contracted multiple peer review services but only presents the most favorable one.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] An alternative or complementary model for achieving peer review is for the author to pay to have it undertaken.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] An example of such a service provider was Rubriq (2013–2017), which financially compensated peer reviewers for reviewing each work that they were assigned.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The phrase *internal peer review* is also used to describe post-submission review by a journal's editors, before sending them out for external peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The *Health Policy and Planning* journal, for example, reports that 60% of submitted articles are rejected by the editors because the submissions are not appropriate for the journal (e.g., the submitted paper does not discuss any health policies).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For most scholarly publications, the identity of the reviewers is kept anonymised (also called "blind peer review").
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The alternative, *attributed peer review* involves revealing the identities of the reviewers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Some reviewers choose to waive their right to anonymity, even when the journal's default format is blind peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In anonymous peer review, reviewers are known to the journal editor or conference organiser but their names are not given to the article's author.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In some cases, the author's identity can also be anonymised for the review process, with identifying information stripped from the document before review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The system is intended to reduce or eliminate bias.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Some experts proposed blind review procedures for reviewing controversial research topics.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Critics of the double-blind review process point out that, despite any editorial effort to ensure anonymity, the process often fails to do so, since certain approaches, methods, writing styles, notations, etc., point to a certain group of people in a research stream, and even to a particular person.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In many fields of "big science", the publicly available operation schedules of major equipments, such as telescopes or synchrotrons, would make the authors' names obvious to anyone who would care to look them up.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Proponents of double-blind review argue that it performs no worse than single-blind, and that it generates a perception of fairness and equality in academic funding and publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Single-blind review is strongly dependent upon the goodwill of the participants, but no more so than double-blind review with easily identified authors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] As an alternative to single-blind and double-blind review, authors and reviewers are encouraged to declare their conflicts of interest when the names of authors and sometimes reviewers are known to the other.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The incentive for reviewers to declare their conflicts of interest is a matter of professional ethics and individual integrity.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Even when the reviews are not public, they are still a matter of record and the reviewer's credibility depends upon how they represent themselves among their peers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Some software engineering journals, such as the *IEEE Transactions on Software Engineering*, use non-blind reviews with reporting to editors of conflicts of interest by both authors and reviewers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] A more rigorous standard of accountability is known as an audit.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Because reviewers are not paid, they cannot be expected to put as much time and effort into a review as an audit requires.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The traditional anonymous peer review has been criticized for its lack of accountability, the possibility of abuse by reviewers or by those who manage the peer review process (that is, journal editors), its possible bias, and its inconsistency, alongside other flaws.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Eugene Koonin, a senior investigator at the National Center for Biotechnology Information, asserts that the system has "well-known ills" and advocates "open peer review".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Open peer review is the various possible modifications of the traditional scholarly peer review process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Open reports: Review reports are published alongside the relevant article (rather than being kept confidential).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Open participation: The wider community (and not just invited reviewers) are able to contribute to the review process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] These modifications are supposed to address various perceived shortcomings of the traditional scholarly peer review process, in particular its lack of transparency, lack of incentives, wastefulness, bullying and harassment.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In transparent peer review the documents relating to the publication of the paper are published alongside the paper.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] This includes the initial report made by the peer reviewer, the authors' response to it, and the acceptance letter by the editor.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The names of the reviewers may still be kept anonymous even in transparent peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The process of peer review is not restricted to the publication process managed by academic journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In particular, some forms of peer review can occur before an article is submitted to a journal and/or after it is published by the journal.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Manuscripts are typically reviewed by colleagues before submission, and if the manuscript is uploaded to preprint servers, such as ArXiv, BioRxiv or SSRN, researchers can read and comment on the manuscript.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The practice to upload to preprint servers, and the activity of discussion heavily depend on the field, and it allows an *open pre-publication peer review*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The advantage of this method is speed and transparency of the review process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Anyone can give feedback, typically in form of comments, and typically not anonymously.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] These comments are also public, and can be responded to, therefore author-reviewer communication is not restricted to the typical 2–4 rounds of exchanges in traditional publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The authors can incorporate comments from a wide range of people instead of feedback from the typically 3–4 reviewers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The disadvantage is that a far larger number of papers are presented to the community without any guarantee on quality.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] After a manuscript is published, the process of peer review continues as publications are read, known as **post-publication peer review**.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Readers will often send letters to the editor of a journal, or correspond with the editor via an on-line journal club.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In this way, all "peers" may offer review and critique of published literature.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The introduction of the "epub ahead of print" practice in many journals has made possible the simultaneous publication of unsolicited letters to the editor together with the original paper in the print issue.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] A variation on this theme is **open peer commentary**, in which commentaries from specialists are solicited on published articles and the authors are invited to respond.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Journals using this process solicit and publish non-anonymous commentaries on the "target paper" together with the paper, and with original authors' reply as a matter of course.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Open peer commentary was first implemented by the anthropologist Sol Tax, who founded the journal *Current Anthropology* in 1957.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The journal *Behavioral and Brain Sciences*, published by Cambridge University Press, was founded by Stevan Harnad in 1978 and modeled on *Current Anthropology*'s open peer commentary feature.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] *Psycoloquy* (1990–2002) was based on the same feature, but this time implemented online.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Since 2016 open peer commentary is also provided by the journal *Animal Sentience*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] In addition to journals hosting their own articles' reviews, there are also external, independent websites dedicated to post-publication peer-review, such as *PubPeer* which allows anonymous commenting of published literature and pushes authors to answer these comments.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] It has been suggested that post-publication reviews from these sites should be editorially considered as well.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The megajournals *F1000Research* and *ScienceOpen* publish openly both the identity of the reviewers and the reviewer's report alongside the article.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Some journals use post-publication peer review as formal review method, instead of pre-publication review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] This was first introduced in 2001, by *Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics* (ACP).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] More recently *F1000Research, Qeios, and* *ScienceOpen* were launched as megajournals with post-publication review as formal review method.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] At *ACP,* *F1000Research, and Qeios* peer reviewers are formally invited, much like at pre-publication review journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Articles that pass peer review at those three journals are included in external scholarly databases.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Recent research has called attention to the use of social media technologies and science blogs as a means of informal, post-publication peer review, as in the case of the #arseniclife (or GFAJ-1) controversy.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Ultimately, the controversy surrounding the article attracted media attention, and one of the most vocal scientific critics – Rosemary Redfield – formally published in July 2012 regarding her and her colleagues' unsuccessful attempt to replicate the NASA scientists' original findings.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Studies which report a positive or statistically significant result are far more likely to be published than ones which do not.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] A counter-measure to this positivity bias is to hide or make unavailable the results in the paper, making journal acceptance more like scientific grant agencies reviewing research proposals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] Only once the proposed hypothesis and methodology have been accepted by reviewers, the authors would collect the data or analyze previously collected data.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] A limited variant of a pre-accepted article was *The Lancet's* study protocol review from 1997 to 2015 reviewed and published randomized trial protocols with a guarantee that the eventual paper would at least be sent out to peer review rather than immediately rejected.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] For example, *Nature Human Behaviour* has adopted the registered report format, as it "shift[s] the emphasis from the results of research to the questions that guide the research and the methods used to answer them".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] The *European Journal of Personality* defines this format: "In a registered report, authors create a study proposal that includes theoretical and empirical background, research questions/hypotheses, and pilot data (if available).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p01] These findings suggest that when the initial study plan is accepted for publication, there may be a reduced incentive to change preregistered plans.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Scholarly peer review has been subject to several criticisms, and various proposals for reforming the system have been suggested over the years.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Many studies have emphasized the problems inherent to the process of peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Moreover, Ragone et al. have shown that there is a low correlation between peer review outcomes and the future impact measured by citations.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Various biomedical editors in particular have expressed criticism of peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] To an outsider, the anonymous, pre-publication peer review process is opaque.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Certain journals are accused of not carrying out stringent peer review in order to more easily expand their customer base, particularly in journals where authors pay a fee before publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Brezis and Birukou have further argued that that the process is weakened by the fact that reviewers are not investing the same amount of time to analyze the projects.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] This heterogeneity among referees, the two argue, will lead to seriously affect the whole peer review process, and will lead to main arbitrariness in the results of the process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A 2024 review focused on economics identified several recurring concerns in the field’s peer-review process, including referee overreach, strategic refereeing and conflicts of interest, prestige bias, and noisy review outcomes.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Peer review publication is a common requirement for academic tenure.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] This requirement has been criticised on cultural grounds.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In 2011, University of British Columbia assistant law professor, Lorna McCue, argued that emphasis on peer review publication was culturally inappropriate as it did not recognize the importance of Indigenous oral traditions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In 2018, the British Columbia Human Rights Tribunal found that this complaint was not justified .
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] There is an ongoing discussion about a peer-review crisis.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In 2022 *Inside Higher Ed* reported a serious shortage of scholars to review submitted articles and bigger structural problems amplified by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Brezis and Birukou have argued that a major issues in the peer process is that referees display homophily in their taste and perception of innovative ideas.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] This means that reviewers who are developing conventional ideas tend to give low grades to more innovative projects, while reviewers who develop innovative ideas tend, by homophily, to give higher grades to innovative projects.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Similarly, peer review is more problematic when choosing the projects to be funded since innovative projects are not highly ranked in the existing peer-review process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The peer-review process leads to conformity, i.e., the selection of less controversial projects and papers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] This may even influence the type of proposals scholars will propose, since scholars need to find financing for their research as discussed by Martin, 1997: "A common informal view is that it is easier to obtain funds for conventional projects.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Those who are eager to get funding are not likely to propose radical or unorthodox projects.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Since you don't know who the referees are going to be, it is best to assume that they are middle-of-the-road.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Therefore, the middle-of-the-road application is safer".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Researchers have peer-reviewed manuscripts prior to publishing them in a variety of ways since the 18th century.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The main goal of this practice is to improve the relevance and accuracy of scientific discussions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Even though experts often criticize peer review for a number of reasons, the process is still often considered the "gold standard" of science.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Occasionally however, peer review approves studies that are later found to be wrong and rarely deceptive or fraudulent results are discovered prior to publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Thus, there seems to be an element of discord between the ideology behind and the practice of peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] By failing to effectively communicate that peer review is imperfect, the message conveyed to the wider public is that studies published in peer-reviewed journals are "true" and that peer review protects the literature from flawed science.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A number of well-established criticisms exist of many elements of peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In the following we describe cases of the wider impact inappropriate peer review can have on public understanding of scientific literature.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Multiple examples across several areas of science find that scientists elevated the importance of peer review for research that was questionable or corrupted.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] For example, climate change deniers have published studies in the *Energy and Environment* journal, attempting to undermine the body of research that shows how human activity impacts the Earth's climate.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Politicians in the United States who reject the established science of climate change have then cited this journal on several occasions in speeches and reports.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] At times, peer review has been exposed as a process that was orchestrated for a preconceived outcome.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] *The New York Times* gained access to confidential peer review documents for studies sponsored by the National Football League (NFL) that were cited as scientific evidence that brain injuries do not cause long-term harm to its players.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] During the peer review process, the authors of the study stated that all NFL players were part of a study, a claim that the reporters found to be false by examining the database used for the research.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Furthermore, *The Times* noted that the NFL sought to legitimize the studies" methods and conclusion by citing a "rigorous, confidential peer-review process" despite evidence that some peer reviewers seemed "desperate" to stop their publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Recent research has also demonstrated that widespread industry funding for published medical research often goes undeclared and that such conflicts of interest are not appropriately addressed by peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Conflict of interest is less likely to be picked up in double-blinded reviews since the reviewer does not know the identity of the authors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Another problem that peer review fails to catch is ghostwriting, a process by which companies draft articles for academics who then publish them in journals, sometimes with little or no changes.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] These studies can then be used for political, regulatory and marketing purposes.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In 2010, the US Senate Finance Committee released a report that found this practice was widespread, that it corrupted the scientific literature and increased prescription rates.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Ghostwritten articles have appeared in dozens of journals, involving professors at several universities.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] It is all we have, and it is hard to imagine how we would get along without it".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] But these subtleties are lost on the general public, who are often misled into thinking that being published in a journal with peer review is the "gold standard" and can erroneously equate published research with the truth.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Thus, more care must be taken over how peer review, and the results of peer-reviewed research, are communicated to non-specialist audiences; particularly during a time in which a range of technical changes and a deeper appreciation of the complexities of peer review are emerging.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] This will be needed as the scholarly publishing system has to confront wider issues such as retractions and replication or reproducibility "crises".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Peer review is often considered integral to scientific discourse in one form or another.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Its gatekeeping role is supposed to be necessary to maintain the quality of the scientific literature and avoid a risk of unreliable results, inability to separate signal from noise, and slow scientific progress.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Shortcomings of peer review have been met with calls for even stronger filtering and more gatekeeping.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A common argument in favor of such initiatives is the belief that this filter is needed to maintain the integrity of the scientific literature.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Calls for more oversight have at least two implications that are counterintuitive of what is known to be true scholarship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The belief that scholars need a "guardian" to make sure they are doing good work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Others argue that authors most of all have a vested interest in the quality of a particular piece of work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Instead, the credibility conferred by the "peer-reviewed" label could diminish what Feynman calls the *culture of doubt* necessary for science to operate a self-correcting, truth-seeking process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The effects of this can be seen in the ongoing replication crisis, hoaxes, and widespread outrage over the inefficacy of the current system.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] It's common to think that more oversight is the answer, as peer reviewers are not at all lacking in skepticism.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] But the issue is not the skepticism shared by the select few who determine whether an article passes through the filter.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] It is the validation, and accompanying lack of skepticism, that comes afterwards.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Here again more oversight only adds to the impression that peer review ensures quality, thereby further diminishing the culture of doubt and counteracting the spirit of scientific inquiry.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Quality research – even some of our most fundamental scientific discoveries – dates back centuries, long before peer review took its current form.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Whatever peer review existed centuries ago, it took a different form than it does in modern times, without the influence of large, commercial publishing companies or a pervasive culture of publish or perish.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Though in its initial conception it was often a laborious and time-consuming task, researchers took peer review on nonetheless, not out of obligation but out of duty to uphold the integrity of their own scholarship.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] They managed to do so, for the most part, without the aid of centralised journals, editors, or any formalised or institutionalised process whatsoever.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Such modern technology includes posting results to preprint servers, preregistration of studies, open peer review, and other open science practices.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Jon Tennant also argues that the outcry over the inefficiencies of traditional journals centers on their inability to provide rigorous enough scrutiny, and the outsourcing of critical thinking to a concealed and poorly-understood process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Thus, the assumption that journals and peer review are required to protect scientific integrity seems to undermine the very foundations of scholarly inquiry.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] To test the hypothesis that filtering is indeed unnecessary to quality control, many of the traditional publication practices would need to be redesigned, editorial boards repurposed if not disbanded, and authors granted control over the peer review of their own work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Putting authors in charge of their own peer review is seen as serving a dual purpose.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] On one hand, it removes the conferral of quality within the traditional system, thus eliminating the prestige associated with the simple act of publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Perhaps paradoxically, the removal of this barrier might actually result in an increase of the quality of published work, as it eliminates the cachet of publishing for its own sake.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] On the other hand, readers know that there is no filter so they must interpret anything they read with a healthy dose of skepticism, thereby naturally restoring the culture of doubt to scientific practice.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In addition to concerns about the quality of work produced by well-meaning researchers, there are concerns that a truly open system would allow the literature to be populated with junk and propaganda by those with a vested interest in certain issues.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A counterargument is that the conventional model of peer review diminishes the healthy skepticism that is a hallmark of scientific inquiry, and thus confers credibility upon subversive attempts to infiltrate the literature.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Allowing such "junk" to be published could make individual articles less reliable but render the overall literature more robust by fostering a "culture of doubt".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The interposition of editors and reviewers between authors and readers may enable the intermediators to act as gatekeepers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Some sociologists of science argue that peer review makes the ability to publish susceptible to control by elites and to personal jealousy.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The peer review process may sometimes impede progress and may be biased against novelty.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A linguistic analysis of review reports suggests that reviewers focus on rejecting the applications by searching for weak points, and not on finding the high-risk/high-gain groundbreaking ideas that may be in the proposal.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Reviewers tend to be especially critical of conclusions that contradict their own views, and lenient towards those that match them.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] At the same time, established scientists are more likely than others to be sought out as referees, particularly by high-prestige journals/publishers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] As a result, ideas that harmonize with the established experts' are more likely to see print and to appear in premier journals than are iconoclastic or revolutionary ones.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] This accords with Thomas Kuhn's well-known observations regarding scientific revolutions.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A theoretical model has been established whose simulations imply that peer review and over-competitive research funding foster mainstream opinion to monopoly.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Criticisms of traditional anonymous peer review allege that it lacks accountability, can lead to abuse by reviewers, and may be biased and inconsistent.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] There have also been suggestions of gender bias in peer review, with male authors being likely to receive more favorable treatment.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A 2021 study found in some respects bias in favor of female authors and found no evidence for bias in favor of male authors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Political bias can be found in reviewer evaluations.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Most academic publishers do not financially compensate reviewers for their participation in the peer-review process, which has been criticized by the academic community.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Whereas some publishers have contended that it is economically not feasible to pay reviewers, some journals have started to pay reviewers through platforms such as Research Square when they are unable to receive free reviews.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Other publishers such as Advances.in have made paying reviewers an inherent part of their business model.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Some critics of open access (OA) journals have argued that, compared to traditional subscription journals, open access journals might utilize substandard or less formal peer review practices, and, as a consequence, the quality of scientific work in such journals will suffer.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Peer review fails when a peer-reviewed article contains fundamental errors that undermine at least one of its main conclusions and that could have been identified by more careful reviewers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Many journals have no procedure to deal with peer review failures beyond publishing letters to the editor.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Peer review in scientific journals assumes that the article reviewed has been honestly prepared.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The process occasionally detects fraud, but is not designed to do so.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] When peer review fails and a paper is published with fraudulent or otherwise irreproducible data, the paper may be retracted.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A 1998 experiment on peer review with a fictitious manuscript found that peer reviewers failed to detect some manuscript errors and the majority of reviewers may not notice that the conclusions of the paper are unsupported by its results.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] There have been instances where peer review was claimed to be performed but in fact was not; this has been documented in some predatory open access journals (e.g., the "Who's Afraid of Peer Review?" affair) or in the case of sponsored Elsevier journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In November 2014, an article in *Nature* exposed that some academics were submitting fake contact details for recommended reviewers to journals, so that if the publisher contacted the recommended reviewer, they were the original author reviewing their own work under a fake name.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The Committee on Publication Ethics issued a statement warning of the fraudulent practice.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In March 2015, BioMed Central retracted 43 articles and Springer retracted 64 papers in 10 journals in August 2015.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] *Tumor Biology* journal is another example of peer review fraud.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In 2020, the *Journal of Nanoparticle Research* fell victim to an "organized rogue editor network", who impersonated respected academics, got a themed issue created, and got 19 substandard articles published (out of 80 submitted).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] The journal was praised for dealing with the scam openly and transparently.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In 2023, the journal *Airbursts and Cratering Impacts* was founded by members of the Comet Research Group to publish "cutting-edge, impact-related investigations" that among other things, according to its web page, "have been rejected by other journals".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] It has been described as a "vanity journal", where authors "self-edit, self-review and republish versions of their own retracted papers and manuscripts that have repeatedly been rejected by legitimate journals".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Reviewers generally lack access to raw data, but do see the full text of the manuscript, and are typically familiar with recent publications in the area.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Thus, they are in a better position to detect plagiarism of prose than fraudulent data.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] A few cases of such textual plagiarism by historians, for instance, have been widely publicized.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] On the scientific side, a poll of 3,247 scientists funded by the U.S.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] National Institutes of Health found 0.3% admitted faking data and 1.4% admitted plagiarism.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Additionally, 4.7% of the same poll admitted to self-plagiarism or autoplagiarism, in which an author republishes the same material, data, or text, without citing their earlier work.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Self-plagiarisms are less likely to be detected in double-blinded peer reviews.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Other attempts to reform the peer review process originate among others from the fields of metascience and journalology.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Reformers seek to increase the reliability and efficiency of the peer review process and to provide it with a scientific foundation.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Alternatives to common peer review practices have been put to the test, in particular *open peer review*, where the comments are visible to readers, generally with the identities of the peer reviewers disclosed as well, e.g., F1000, *eLife*, *BMJ*, and BioMed Central.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In the case of eLife, peer review is used not for deciding whether to publish an article, but for assessing its importance and reliability.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Likewise, the recognition and recruitment of peer reviewers continues to be a significant issue in the field of scholarly publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] In 2017, the Higher School of Economics in Moscow unveiled a "Monument to an Anonymous Peer Reviewer".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] It takes the form of a large concrete cube, or dice, with "Accept", "Minor Changes", "Major Changes", "Revise and Resubmit" and "Reject" on its five visible sides.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-peer-review-p02] Sociologist Igor Chirikov, who devised the monument, said that while researchers have a love-hate relationship with peer review, peer reviewers nonetheless do valuable but mostly invisible work, and the monument is a tribute to them.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Most established academic disciplines have their own journals and other outlets for publication, although many academic journals are somewhat interdisciplinary, and publish work from several distinct fields or subfields.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] There is also a tendency for existing journals to divide into specialized sections as the field itself becomes more specialized.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Along with the variation in review and publication procedures, the kinds of publications that are accepted as contributions to knowledge or research differ greatly among fields and subfields.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In the sciences, the desire for statistically significant results leads to publication bias.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Academic publishing is undergoing major changes as it makes the transition from the print to the electronic format.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Business models are different in the electronic environment.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Since the early 1990s, licensing of electronic resources, particularly journals, has been very common.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] An important trend, particularly with respect to journals in the sciences, is open access via the Internet.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In open access publishing, a journal article is made available free for all on the web by the publisher at the time of publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Both open and closed journals are sometimes funded by the author paying an article processing charge, thereby shifting some fees from the reader to the researcher or their funder.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Many open or closed journals fund their operations without such fees and others use them in predatory publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The Internet has facilitated open access self-archiving, in which authors themselves make a copy of their published articles available free for all on the web.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Some important results in mathematics have been published only on arXiv.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The *Journal des sçavans* (later spelled *Journal des savants*), established by Denis de Sallo, was the earliest academic journal published in Europe.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Its content included obituaries of famous men, church history, and legal reports.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The first issue appeared as a twelve-page quarto pamphlet on Monday, 5 January 1665, shortly before the first appearance of the *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society*, on 6 March 1665.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The publishing of academic journals has started in the 17th century, and expanded greatly in the 19th.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] At that time, the act of publishing academic inquiry was controversial and widely ridiculed.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] It was not at all unusual for a new discovery to be announced as a monograph, reserving priority for the discoverer, but indecipherable for anyone not in on the secret: both Isaac Newton and Leibniz used this approach.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Merton, a sociologist, found that 92% of cases of simultaneous discovery in the 17th century ended in dispute.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The number of disputes dropped to 72% in the 18th century, 59% by the latter half of the 19th century, and 33% by the first half of the 20th century.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The Royal Society was steadfast in its not-yet-popular belief that science could only move forward through a transparent and open exchange of ideas backed by experimental evidence.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Early scientific journals embraced several models: some were run by a single individual who exerted editorial control over the contents, often simply publishing extracts from colleagues' letters, while others employed a group decision-making process, more closely aligned to modern peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] It was not until the middle of the 20th century that peer review became the standard.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The COVID-19 pandemic hijacked the entire world of basic and clinical science, with unprecedented shifts in funding priorities worldwide and a boom in medical publishing, accompanied by an unprecedented increase in the number of publications.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Preprint servers became much more popular during the pandemic, and the Covid situation also had an impact on traditional peer-review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The pandemic has also deepened the concentration of science-publishing in Western countries.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Of the 720000 authors of papers published about COVID-19 before August 2021, nearly 270000 were from the US, the UK, Italy or Spain.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In the 1960s and 1970s, commercial publishers began to selectively acquire "top-quality" journals that were previously published by nonprofit academic societies.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] When the commercial publishers raised the subscription prices significantly, they lost little of the market, due to the inelastic demand for these journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Although there are over 2,000 publishers, five for-profit companies (Reed Elsevier, Springer Science+Business Media, Wiley-Blackwell, Taylor & Francis, and SAGE) accounted for 50% of articles published in 2013.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] These factors have contributed to the "serials crisis" – total expenditures on serials increased 7.6% per year from 1986 to 2005, yet the number of serials purchased increased an average of only 1.9% per year.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Unlike most industries, in academic publishing the two most important inputs are provided "virtually free of charge".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] These are the articles and the peer review process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Publishers argue that they add value to the publishing process through support to the peer review group, including stipends, as well as through typesetting, printing, and web publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Investment analysts, however, have been skeptical of the value added by for-profit publishers, as exemplified by a 2005 Deutsche Bank analysis which stated that "we believe the publisher adds relatively little value to the publishing process...
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Studies found the topic-specificity of scientific journals together with high impact factor expectations for career advancement some scientists have limited options in which journals to publish their work, resulting in limited competition in parts of academic publishing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] A crisis in academic publishing is "widely perceived"; the apparent crisis has to do with the combined pressure of budget cuts at universities and increased costs for journals (the serials crisis).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The university budget cuts have reduced library budgets and reduced subsidies to university-affiliated publishers.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The humanities have been particularly affected by the pressure on university publishers, which are less able to publish monographs when libraries can not afford to purchase them.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] For example, the ARL found that in "1986, libraries spent 44% of their budgets on books compared with 56% on journals; twelve years later, the ratio had skewed to 28% and 72%." Meanwhile, monographs are increasingly expected for tenure in the humanities.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In 2002 the Modern Language Association expressed hope that electronic publishing would solve the issue.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In 2009 and 2010, surveys and reports found that libraries faced continuing budget cuts, with one survey in 2009 finding that 36% of UK libraries had their budgets cut by 10% or more, compared to 29% with increased budgets.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In the 2010s, libraries began more aggressive cost cutting with the leverage of open access and open data.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Data analysis with open source tools like Unpaywall Journals empowered library systems in reducing their subscription costs by 70% with the cancellation of the big deal with publishers like Elsevier.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Several models are being investigated, such as open publication models or adding community-oriented features.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] It is also considered that "Online scientific interaction outside the traditional journal space is becoming more and more important to academic communication".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In addition, experts have suggested measures to make the publication process more efficient in disseminating new and important findings by evaluating the worthiness of publication on the basis of the significance and novelty of the research finding.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In academic publishing, a paper is an academic work that is usually published in an academic journal.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] It contains original research results or reviews existing results.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Such a paper, also called an article, will only be considered valid if it undergoes a process of peer review by one or more *referees* (who are academics in the same field) who check that the content of the paper is suitable for publication in the journal.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] A paper may undergo a series of reviews, revisions, and re-submissions before finally being accepted or rejected for publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] This process typically takes several months.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Next, there is often a delay of many months (or in some fields, over a year) before an accepted manuscript appears.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] This is particularly true for the most popular journals where the number of accepted articles often outnumbers the space for printing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Due to this, many academics self-archive a 'preprint' or 'postprint' copy of their paper for free download from their personal or institutional website.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Some journals, particularly newer ones, are now published in electronic form only.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Paper journals are now generally made available in electronic form as well, both to individual subscribers, and to libraries.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Journals having this delayed availability are sometimes called delayed open access journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Ellison in 2011 reported that in economics the dramatic increase in opportunities to publish results online has led to a decline in the use of peer-reviewed articles.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Note: Law review is the generic term for a journal of legal scholarship in the United States, often operating by rules radically different from those for most other academic journals.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Peer review is a central concept for most academic publishing; other scholars in a field must find a work sufficiently high in quality for it to merit publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] A group of experts reviews the manuscript regarding its originality, correctness, and relevance.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] A secondary benefit of the process is an indirect guard against plagiarism since reviewers are usually familiar with the sources consulted by the author(s).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The origins of routine peer review for submissions dates to 1752 when the Royal Society of London took over official responsibility for *Philosophical Transactions.* However, there were some earlier examples.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] While journal editors largely agree the system is essential to quality control in terms of rejecting poor quality work, there have been examples of important results that are turned down by one journal before being taken to others.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] "Confirmatory bias" is the unconscious tendency to accept reports which support the reviewer's views and to downplay those which do not.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Experimental studies show the problem exists in peer reviewing.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The possibility of rejections of papers is an important aspect in peer review.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The evaluation of quality of journals is based also on *rejection rate*.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The best journals have the highest rejection rates (around 90–95%).
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] American Psychological Association journals' rejection rates ranged "from a low of 35 per cent to a high of 85 per cent." The complement is called "acceptance rate".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The process of academic publishing, which begins when authors submit a manuscript to a publisher, is divided into two distinct phases: peer review and production.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The process of peer review is organized by the journal editor and is complete when the content of the article, together with any associated images, data, and supplementary material are accepted for publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The peer review process is increasingly managed online, through the use of proprietary systems, commercial software packages, or open source and free software.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] A manuscript undergoes one or more rounds of review; after each round, the author(s) of the article modify their submission in line with the reviewers' comments; this process is repeated until the editor is satisfied and the work is accepted.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The production process, controlled by a production editor or publisher, then takes an article through copy editing, typesetting, inclusion in a specific issue of a journal, and then printing and online publication.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Academic copy editing seeks to ensure that an article conforms to the journal's house style, that all of the referencing and labelling is correct, and that the text is consistent and legible; often this work involves substantive editing and negotiating with the authors.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] Because the work of academic copy editors can overlap with that of authors' editors, editors employed by journal publishers often refer to themselves as "manuscript editors".
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] During this process, copyright is often transferred from the author to the publisher.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In the late 20th century author-produced camera-ready copy has been replaced by electronic formats such as PDF.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The author will review and correct proofs at one or more stages in the production process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] The proof correction cycle has historically been labour-intensive as handwritten comments by authors and editors are manually transcribed by a proof reader onto a clean version of the proof.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] In the early 21st century, this process was streamlined by the introduction of e-annotations in Microsoft Word, Adobe Acrobat, and other programs, but it still remained a time-consuming and error-prone process.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] At the end of this process, a final version of record is published.
[src:academic-publishing/academic-publishing] From time to time some published journal articles have been retracted for different reasons, including research misconduct.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] AMiner (ArnetMiner) is designed to search and perform data mining operations against academic publications on the Internet, using social network analysis to identify connections between researchers, conferences, and publications.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] This allows it to provide services such as expert finding, geographic search, trend analysis, reviewer recommendation, association search, course search, academic performance evaluation, and topic modeling.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] AMiner was created as a research project in social influence analysis, social network ranking, and social network extraction.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] A number of peer-reviewed papers have been published arising from the development of the system.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] It has been in operation for more than three years, and has indexed 130,000,000 researchers and more than 265 million publications.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] The research was funded by the Chinese National High-tech R&D Program and the National Science Foundation of China.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] AMiner is commonly used in academia to identify relationships between and draw statistical correlations about research and researchers.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] It has attracted more than 10 million independent IP accesses from 220 countries and regions.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] The product has been used in Elsevier's SciVerse platform, and academic conferences such as SIGKDD, ICDM, PKDD, WSDM.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] AMiner automatically extracts the researcher profile from the web.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] It collects and identifies the relevant pages, then uses a unified approach to extract data from the identified documents.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] It also extracts publications from online digital libraries using heuristic rules.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] It integrates the extracted researchers' profiles and the extracted publications.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] It employs the researcher name as the identifier.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] A probabilistic framework has been proposed to deal with the name ambiguity problem in the integration.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] The integrated data is stored into a researcher network knowledge base (RNKB).
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] The principal other products in the area are Google Scholar, Elsevier's Scirus, and the open source project CiteSeer.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] It was initiated and created by professor Jie Tang from Tsinghua University, China.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] AMiner published several datasets for academic research purpose, including Open Academic Graph, DBLP+citation (a data set augmenting citations into the DBLP data from Digital Bibliography & Library Project), Name Disambiguation, Social Tie Analysis.
[src:academic-publishing/aminer-database] For more available datasets and source codes for research, please refer to.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The APA became involved in journal publishing in 1923.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] In 1929, an APA committee had a seven-page writer's guide published in the *Psychological Bulletin*.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] In 1944, a 32-page guide appeared as an article in the same journal.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The first edition of the *APA Publication Manual* was published in 1952 as a 61-page supplement to the *Psychological Bulletin*, marking the beginning of a recognized "APA style".
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The initial edition went through two revisions: one in 1957, and one in 1967.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The increasing length of the guidelines and its transformation into a manual have been accompanied by increasingly explicit prescriptions about many aspects of acceptable work.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The earliest editions were controlled by a group of field leaders who were behaviorist in orientation and the manual has continued to foster that ideology, even as it has influenced many other fields.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] According to the American Psychological Association, APA format can make the point of an argument clear and simple to the reader.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] Particularly influential were the "Guidelines for Nonsexist Language in APA Journals", first published as a modification to the 1974 edition, which provided practical alternatives to sexist language then in common usage.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The guidelines for reducing bias in language have been updated over the years and presently provide practical guidance for writing about age, disability, gender, participation in research, race and ethnicity, sexual orientation, socioeconomic status, and intersectionality (APA, 2020, Chapter 5).
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The seventh edition of the *Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association* is the current one, published in October 2019.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The goal of the book is to help people become better writers and communicators by promoting clarity, precision, and inclusivity.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The manual has new resources for students, including a student title page, student paper formats, and student-related reference formats such as classroom course pack material and classroom website sources.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The book also includes new journal article reporting standards for qualitative and mixed methods research in addition to updated standards for quantitative research.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The bias-free language guidelines have also been updated to reflect current best practices for talking about people's personal characteristics.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The manual addresses accessibility for people with disabilities for the first time.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] APA worked with accessibility experts to ensure APA style is accessible.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] For example, the in-text citation format is shortened so that the citations are easier to read for people who, for example, use screen readers or have cognitive disabilities.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] Running heads are used in papers that follow APA Style.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The running head is an abbreviated version of the paper title that is included in the header of professional papers along with the page number.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] In student papers, the page number is placed in the header but the page title is not, unless otherwise stated by the course instructor or educational institution.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The manual has hundreds of reference examples, including formats for audiovisual media, social media, and webpages.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] There are many sample tables and figures, including basic student-friendly examples such as bar graphs.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] There are also sample papers for professionals and students.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] Since the seventh edition, APA also provides an APA Style website and APA Style blog to help people with APA style and answer common questions.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The sixth edition of the *Publication Manual of the American Psychological Association* was in effect from 2009 to 2019, after four years of development.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] To accomplish these revisions, the Task Force appointed working groups of four to nine members in seven areas: bias-free language, ethics, graphics, Journal Article Reporting Standards, references, statistics, and writing style (APA, 2009, pp. xvii–xviii).
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The APA explained the issuing of a new edition only eight years after the fifth edition by pointing to the increased use of online source or online access to academic journals (6th edition, p.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] The sixth edition is accompanied by a style website as well as the APA Style Blog which answers many common questions from users.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] Sample papers in the first printing of the sixth edition contained errors.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] APA staff posted all of the corrections online for free in a single document on October 1, 2009, and shortly thereafter alerted users to the existence of the corrections in an APA blog entry.
[src:academic-publishing/apa-style] All copies of the printing with errors were soon after recalled in 2009 (including those from major retailers such as Amazon.com) and a new printing correcting all the errors, with a copyright date of 2010, was issued.
